ical questions, touching not only on the political implications of religion so important to Hobbes, but also on his attempt to reconstruct Christianity in terms of a materialistic philosophy. He also explores Hobbes's continuous critique of Aristotle and Aristotelian Scholastics, in which Höffe argues that Hobbes and Aristotle have much more in common philosophically than is normally supposed—and certainly more than Hobbes himself acknowledged. Finally, Höffe sketches the influence Hobbes had and continues to have on the development of legal and political philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhilosopherszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPolitical scientists - Great Britain. 0aPolitical scientistszGreat BritainvBiography. 4aPhilosophy : History of Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aWalker, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845767340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438457673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438457673/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles